---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import DocsShell from '~/components/widgets/DocsShell.astro';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Apps — Aitroop Docs',
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <DocsShell current="apps">
    <h1>Apps</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      An App is a chat that has been crystallized into a reusable workflow. A form replaces the
      free-form prompt; the goal stays fixed; every run produces the same shape of result.
    </p>

    <h2>Anatomy</h2>
    <p>An App has three parts. You already know them from <a href="/docs/concepts">Core concepts</a>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>AppInput[]</strong> — the form fields that vary between runs.</li>
      <li><strong>Stage[]</strong> — one or more agent sessions, each with a fixed goal.</li>
      <li><strong>Artifact[]</strong> — the deliverable each Stage produces.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Creating an App</h2>
    <p>There are two ways:</p>

    <h3>From a chat (recommended)</h3>
    <p>
      Open a chat, do the work, click <strong>Save as App</strong>. The platform proposes inputs based
      on what varied in the conversation, freezes the goal, and gives you a draft App to review.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is the right path the vast majority of the time. The agent has already seen what you actually
      want; the saved App inherits that context.
    </p>

    <h3>From a template</h3>
    <p>
      The use case packs ship pre-built Apps you can install with one click. From the App library,
      click <strong>Add → From template</strong>, pick the App, and it appears in your library.
      You can fork and edit any template.
    </p>

    <h2>The App editor</h2>
    <p>When you save a chat or open an existing App for editing, the editor has four tabs:</p>

    <h3>Inputs</h3>
    <p>
      The form. Add, remove, and reorder AppInput fields. Each input has a type, a label, an optional
      help string, and optional defaults. Mark inputs as required when the App can't run without them.
    </p>
    <p>
      Common patterns:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>A <code>daterange</code> input for time-windowed reports.</li>
      <li>A <code>select</code> input for output language or output format.</li>
      <li>A <code>connect_file</code> input when the user should pick from their Drive or Notion.</li>
      <li>A <code>file</code> input for one-off uploads (a CSV of leads, a PDF to summarize).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Stages</h3>
    <p>
      The agent's instructions. For single-stage Apps, this is just the goal of the conversation.
      For multi-stage Apps, this is where you wire the output of Stage 1 into the input of Stage 2.
    </p>
    <p>
      Each Stage also declares which Skills and which Connects it needs. Restricting Skills per Stage
      keeps the agent focused — and makes the App's behavior predictable across runs.
    </p>

    <h3>Output</h3>
    <p>
      What the App produces. Pick an Artifact type and, optionally, a schema or layout. The agent will
      conform its final output to this shape — or fail loudly if it can't, which is what you want.
    </p>

    <h3>Settings</h3>
    <p>
      Name, icon, description, and visibility:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Private</strong> — only you can see and run it.</li>
      <li><strong>Team</strong> — visible to everyone in your workspace.</li>
      <li><strong>Public (workspace)</strong> — visible and runnable by anyone in your workspace, including viewers who don't have edit rights.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Running an App</h2>
    <p>
      Click <strong>Run</strong>. Fill in the form. The agent executes each Stage in order, and the
      final Artifact appears in the preview pane. Every run is logged: who ran it, with what inputs,
      what it produced, and any errors.
    </p>
    <p>
      Runs are isolated. Two teammates running the same App at the same time never interfere with each
      other. Each run gets its own sandbox and its own Artifact history.
    </p>

    <h2>Versioning</h2>
    <p>
      Every <strong>Save</strong> on an App creates a new version. The App page shows the version
      history and a diff between any two versions. Scheduled runs always use the latest version
      unless you pin a specific version on the schedule.
    </p>
    <p>
      Older versions don't disappear — you can revert at any time, or compare what an App looked like
      last month with what it looks like today.
    </p>

    <h2>Sharing and access</h2>
    <p>
      Workspace-visible Apps appear in your teammates' App library. Anyone with view access can run
      the App and see its results. Edit access is separately granted — running an App and modifying
      it are different permissions.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you fork someone else's App, you get a copy with your own version history. Changes you make
      to your fork don't propagate back to the original.
    </p>

    <h2>Multi-stage Apps</h2>
    <p>
      Most Apps need exactly one Stage. Use multi-stage when the natural shape of the work is a
      pipeline — each step produces something the next step consumes.
    </p>
    <p>Example: a Lead Outreach App with three stages.</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Stage 1 — Find.</strong> Input is an ICP description. Output is a list of companies (CSV).</li>
      <li><strong>Stage 2 — Enrich.</strong> Input is Stage 1's CSV. Output is the same list with verified emails, recent news, and a personalization hook (CSV).</li>
      <li><strong>Stage 3 — Draft.</strong> Input is Stage 2's CSV. Output is one outreach email per row (markdown).</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Each Stage is independently re-runnable. If Stage 3's drafts aren't good, you can re-run just
      Stage 3 with a different prompt — without re-finding and re-enriching the leads.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Heuristic.</strong> If a single conversation in chat naturally has a "ok now do step 2 with that"
      moment, the saved App probably wants to be multi-stage. If the chat is one continuous thought, one
      Stage is enough.
    </div>

    <h2>When an App fails</h2>
    <p>
      A failed run still produces a record: the inputs it was given, the agent's reasoning trace,
      and the error. Click into the run from the App's history. The fastest fix is usually to
      open the failed run as a chat (the <strong>Debug in chat</strong> action) and continue
      iterating from there.
    </p>
    <p>
      Once you've found the fix, save it back to the App. Future runs pick up the new version.
    </p>

    <div class="next-up">
      <span class="label">Next</span>
      <a href="/docs/skills">Skills — capability modules</a>
    </div>
  </DocsShell>
</Layout>
